00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:29.310
So we decided to
make the Instant

00:18:29.310 --> 00:18:32.530
game available to all users.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:35.760
The question was how to distill
this multifaceted game of base

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:39.810
building, hero collecting,
match-three, and PVP

00:18:39.810 --> 00:18:43.920
into a single,
memorable experience.

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:45.780
That's when we used
our performance data

00:18:45.780 --> 00:18:52.560
to collect our experience
to build an Instant game.

00:18:52.560 --> 00:18:55.320
We partner with the
external developer called

00:18:55.320 --> 00:19:00.390
Seepia Games to build what
we want to be a streamlined,

00:19:00.390 --> 00:19:03.300
optimized but fun
Instant game experience.

00:19:06.120 --> 00:19:10.940
In analyzing the data, we
took away some key learnings.

00:19:10.940 --> 00:19:13.160
First of all, don't cut corners.

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:15.410
In this first
example here, we saw

00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:18.740
that having a
non-optimized tutorial

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:20.510
does not convert
users very well,

00:19:20.510 --> 00:19:24.350
because it left users feeling
confused and frustrated on not

00:19:24.350 --> 00:19:25.580
knowing how to play the game.

00:19:28.220 --> 00:19:31.550
We solved this problem later on
by scaling down the game board

00:19:31.550 --> 00:19:32.930
so that it's easier.

00:19:32.930 --> 00:19:34.550
But that didn't work
out well either,

00:19:34.550 --> 00:19:36.230
because the players
dismissed that

00:19:36.230 --> 00:19:40.430
as being too simple
and too basic.

00:19:40.430 --> 00:19:43.250
And then the final
step was getting

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:46.820
the right mix of an
immersive experience

00:19:46.820 --> 00:19:49.640
that's complex enough to
hold the user's attention

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:53.690
as well as streamlined enough
to play without a long tutorial.

00:19:53.690 --> 00:19:57.260
We also tested to see the
visual appeal of the game.

00:19:57.260 --> 00:19:59.750
We found out that
the players prefer

00:19:59.750 --> 00:20:02.120
battling a dragon
over a random shark

00:20:02.120 --> 00:20:04.370
with knives walking
on the beach.

00:20:04.370 --> 00:20:06.050
So getting the
visual appeal of it

00:20:06.050 --> 00:20:10.800
was just as important as
getting the mechanics right.

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:13.080
We tested many different
levels and bosses.

00:20:13.080 --> 00:20:16.380
And we found that experimenting
with the difficulty

00:20:16.380 --> 00:20:19.230
rate or the win rate was
very important in getting

00:20:19.230 --> 00:20:20.940
the users to convert.

00:20:20.940 --> 00:20:23.760
Our hypothesis was
that, if a user loses,

00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:27.060
he'll be more likely to download
the game and try to beat it.

00:20:27.060 --> 00:20:30.600
So we create two versions
of every single level.

00:20:30.600 --> 00:20:33.210
We've made a hard
one and an easy one.

00:20:33.210 --> 00:20:35.580
And surprisingly,
the easy one was

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:38.265
more effective in converting
users to download.

00:20:41.175 --> 00:20:42.800
Building on the
complexity of the game,

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:45.830
we wanted to create a meta
game for the experience.

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:48.440
So we moved away from
a randomized sequence

00:20:48.440 --> 00:20:53.690
to a more coherent saga map
much like the real game.

00:20:53.690 --> 00:20:57.720
And this experience here
saves your progress.

00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:00.950
So if you play two levels and
then you don't install it,

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:03.200
the next time that you
interact with the Instant game,

00:21:03.200 --> 00:21:07.460
it will take you to the
boss at level three.

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:10.730
Overall, we experimented with
over 30 different versions

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:14.210
to find the right complexity,
length, difficulty,

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:15.560
and visual appeal of the game.

00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:21.250
So if you want to
get started, I would

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:24.700
recommend finding
a developer who's

00:21:24.700 --> 00:21:28.780
experienced in game design and
who has the technical know-how

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:31.480
to build many different
ideas and concepts

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:34.450
and iterate on those
